[normal]Investment[bold]1.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The commitments 
[normal]we 
[normal]made in the Spending Review constitute the biggest ever upgrade of our 
[normal]existing 
[normal]strategic national roads network, tripling annual investment on major roads enhancements from today’s level to over £3bn by 2020/21.
[normal]1.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This 
[normal]will allow us to address the backlog o
[normal]f repairs and deliver a world-class road network that can meet our future needs, transforming performance by 
[normal]improving connectivity, capacity and journey reliability
[normal].
[normal]1.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Investment can also enhance the standard of safety for road users. Our safest roads are t
[normal]hose where we’ve already invested – where junctions are safe, where dual carriageways 
[normal]and motorways 
[normal]take much of the risk out of overtaking and where surfaces and alignments 
[normal]reflect
[normal] modern
[normal] standards
[normal]. For example improving 
[normal]busy 
[normal]at-grade junctions to 
[normal]grade-separated standard would not only mean better flowing traffic but potential safety improvements of 25%-50%.
[normal]1.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In 
[normal]Action for Roads 
[normal]we made clear that a
[normal]ny improvements to the network will need to be made in a way that supports our
[normal] quality of life and sustainability
[normal] outcomes. This means that our vision for roads must 
[normal]b
[normal]e designed to minimise environmental impacts and also address existing problems. The scale of investment which we intend to deliver means that we can afford to invest 
[normal]in environmental safeguards. Greater use of measures such as tunnels, green bridges, noise mitigation
[normal] and measures to control air quality impacts
[normal], means that there 
[normal]does not need to be 
[normal]a stark choice between a well-functioning road network and a well-protec
[normal]ted environment
[normal].
[normal]1.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We will build on and expand existing cooperation with environmental and other 
[normal]bodies
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]roads 
[normal]investment 
[normal]will 
[normal]be accompanied by an aggressive policy of decarbonisation, to address the carbon consequences of motoring and move us to a lowe
[normal]r-impact future.  
[normal]1.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government has made an unprecedented long-term commitment to speeding the transition to low emission motoring in the 
[normal]UK
[normal], including the goal of seeing every car on the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s roads effectively zero emission by 2050.  
[normal]Action for Roads 
[normal]committed an additional £500m to support the switch to the latest ultra-low emission vehicles
[normal], 
[normal]which builds upon existing funding and the
[normal] £1 billion
[normal] 
[normal]of joint industry and g
[normal]overnment funding for an Advanced Propulsion Centre.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]This will 
[normal]support
[normal] 
[normal]improvements
[normal] in air quality 
[normal]as well as
[normal] 
[normal]reductions in
[normal] carbon 
[normal]and greenhouse gas emissions
[normal].
[normal]1.7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We also want to ensure that improvements to 
[normal]the 
[normal]SRN
[normal] 
[normal]take account of the needs of non-motorised users, such as cyclists and walkers. This includes addressing key areas where major
[normal] roads create a barrier to cyclists and walkers, improving safe access for cyclists, especially around junctions, and taking account of their needs in the design of road improvements. 
[normal]The Highways Agency has 
[normal]already 
[normal]been working with Sustrans to 
[normal]identify s
[normal]pecific
[normal] improvements 
[normal]across the
[normal] network. 
